\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Parallax
\f1\b0  is the apparent shift in a star's position against background sources as the Earth orbits the Sun \'97 the most direct distance measurement in all of astronomy, and the 
\f0\b third geometric anchor
\f1\b0  at the bottom of the H0DN distance ladder alongside DEBs and masers.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 The geometry, in one breath\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Earth's orbit has a baseline of 2 AU. As Earth moves from one side of the Sun to the other (six months apart), a nearby star appears to shift against more distant background stars by an angle $2p$, where $p$ is the 
\f0\b parallax angle
\f1\b0 . The distance is then trivially:\
$$d = \\frac\{1 \\text\{ AU\}\}\{p\}$$\
If $p$ is in arcseconds and $d$ is in parsecs, this becomes the famously simple $d \\text\{ [pc]\} = 1/p \\text\{ ["]\}$. (The parsec is 
\f2\i defined
\f1\i0  this way \'97 "parsec" = "parallax of one arcsecond.")\
There is 
\f0\b nothing else
\f1\b0  to it. No standard candle, no calibration, no luminosity assumption, no model atmosphere, no stellar physics whatsoever. You measure an angle and you have a distance. This is why parallax is, conceptually, the most fundamental distance technique \'97 every other method on the H0DN figure ultimately traces back to parallax-calibrated stars somewhere in its history.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 The catch: the angles are tiny\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 A star at 1 pc would have $p = 1$ arcsecond. There are no stars within 1 pc of the Sun (Proxima Centauri, the closest, is at 1.3 pc). At cosmologically interesting distances:\

