\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Future: what changes the parallax anchor\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The big upcoming changes:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Gaia DR4 (~2026)
\f1\b0 : ~30% improvement in parallax precision plus better systematic characterization. The zero-point situation will improve further; expect Cepheid PLR zero point uncertainty to drop by ~25%.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Gaia DR5 (final, ~2030+)
\f1\b0 : end-of-mission catalog with the full ~10.5-year baseline. Roughly 2\'d7 improvement over EDR3.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 JASMINE and Theia and concept missions for IR astrometry
\f1\b0 : would extend parallax work into dust-obscured Galactic plane regions where Gaia is weak. Distant cosmological impact.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Roman Space Telescope's astrometric program
\f1\b0 : not designed primarily for parallax but contributes for some target lists.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The plausible end-state is a Gaia-final-mission Cepheid PLR with parallax-anchor uncertainty well under 1%, making the Cepheid PLR essentially as well-calibrated as it can practically be without going extragalactic. If at that point SH0ES still gives H
\f3 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  \uc0\u8776  73 and Planck still gives 67.4, the tension survives the most natural "fix the calibration" rescue.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Summary \

\f1\b0\fs24 Three quick takeaways:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Parallax is the only anchor that doesn't go extragalactic.
\f1\b0  Its systematics (Gaia zero-point) are completely orthogonal to the systematics of the other two anchors (maser-disk geometry, DEB SBC). For your covariance treatment, treat it as effectively independent of NGC 4258 and the LMC.\
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Parallax only feeds the Cepheid rung.
\f1\b0  Pop-II ladders (TRGB, JAGB, Mira-via-NGC 4258) don't use the MW parallax anchor in any direct way. So if you're partitioning the H0DN measurements into anchor-blocks, parallax goes only with SH0ES-Cepheid, not with CCHP/EDD/Pop-II.\
\ls5\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The three-anchor consistency is the structural argument for SH0ES robustness.
\f1\b0  You can ask whether the LMC distance is wrong, or whether the maser disk model is wrong, or whether Gaia has a residual zero-point \'97 but you can't sensibly argue all three are wrong by exactly the same amount in the same direction. That's the systematics-resistance that lets SH0ES quote 1% precision on H
\f3 \uc0\u8320 
\f1  and have it survive a decade of scrutiny.\
}